The Gospel of Running Away (Newsletter Edition #1)

Hello Friends, David here 👋

Recently, I've been asking myself what the concept of "the gospel" really means. After all, it's a super central idea to Christianity, and thousands of lives have been changed because of it. 1 Corinthians 9:23 shows just how highly valued the gospel was among first-century Christians. Paul says: "I do all things for the sake of the gospel, so that I may become a fellow partaker of it." (cf. Mark 8:35 and 2 Timothy 1:8) This guy wrote this in from a Roman jail cell, waiting for his inevitable execution - just one of many others who suffered immensely but didn't think that his "present suffering [was] worth comparing with the glory that will be revealed." (Romans 8:18) For Christians throughout the ages, the gospel truth is worth more than all else.

But did you know that the word gospel literally means "good news?" That’s because, at it's heart, it’s all about revealing the goodness of God. It’s whole mission is to show you that God is way better than you have ever imagined. Thus, it sums up the whole message of the Bible - to reveal to humanity who God is.

With this newsletter I’d like to pass along some of the things I learn each week about God and His gospel with the hopes that this good news will encourage you to love God more in every stage of your life. I pray you’re blessed!

Willing and Doing

Lately I’ve struggled a lot with doing what's right even when I don't feel like it. For example, even though I know it's good for me to go to bed early so I can get a few hours of sleep in before midnight, more often than not, because I don't feel like going to bed, I get distracted until really late. I feel a lot like Paul when he says "the good that I will to do, I do not do; but the evil I will not to do, that I practice." (Romans 7:19-25) It really does feel "wretched" to know what is right and even want to do what's right, but have my sinful tendencies get in the way of the follow-through.

Then I read in Phillipians 2:12-13 that says I need to “work out [my] own salvation with fear and trembling; for it is God who works in [me] both to will and to do for His good pleasure.” That just made me more confused, because I wasn’t sure what God's part is and what mine is. If, like the passage says, the willing and doing is God’s part, then why does my part involve fear and trembling? Fear and trembling doesn’t sound like the trust and confidence I'm called to as a Christian. Don't get me wrong: I fear and tremble a lot, but more often than not I feel like that unbelief makes me miss out on letting God work. It doesn't feel like my feelings are compatible with God saving me - they just "feel" like they're in the way.

Then we add in Steps to Christ:

“What you need to understand is the true force of the will. This is the governing power in the nature of man, the power of decision, or of choice. Everything depends on the right action of the will. The power of choice God has given to men; it is theirs to exercise. You cannot change your heart, you cannot of yourself give to God its affections; but you can choose to serve Him. You can give Him your will; He will then work in you to will and to do according to His good pleasure.”

SC 47

While it's encouraging to know that my will wields a lot of power, this quote makes me think that my shortcomings mean I’m not trying hard enough. But I have to ask: what am I not trying hard enough to do? How can I give God my affections when they're constantly changing throughout the day? How does my will deal with my feelings?

Then, last week I found this quote by Ellen White that really transformed my perspective on willpower and feelings. It says:

"It is not an abundance of light and evidence that makes the soul free in Christ; it is the rising of the powers and the will and the energies of the soul to cry out sincerely, 'Lord, I believe; help Thou mine unbelief.'"

MYP p. 102.

The implications of what this means totally blows me away. What if freedom in Christ is so much easier than I could have thought? What if giving my will to God doesn’t involve choking out my feelings and suffering through temptation on willpower alone? What if the secret to victory isn’t more information, but running away from my temptations and into God's loving arms?

Let me explain. When I was much younger, I would often run and hide from things I didn’t like. For example, I didn’t like being up in front of people, so during Christmas play practices or church services I would run and hide under tables to avoid the scary stage.

However, our fears don't have to result in embarrassing memories or defeat. What if victory isn’t the result of suppressing our feelings, but comes from using them as motivation to run to Jesus? After all, we’ve just seen in the quote above that what makes the soul free is choosing to run to Jesus. The good news that the gospel reminds us of is that freedom is just a prayer away, and God wants us to run to him no matter what we’re feeling like at the moment.

In fact, I would even say that anger, sadness, pain, happiness, and all our other emotions aren’t inherently wrong or something to be suppressed. I believe that God created them to help us to rely on Him in all things. Anger, for example, was never meant to cause us to act violently or to say things we shouldn’t. It’s purpose is to drive us to God, where we can talk with Him about how we actually feel, and claim His promise of strength.

Thinking back to Philippians 2, it turns out that it's the fear and trembling that allows God to work in us to help us both will and do. It's like what Paul says:

"[God] said to me, 'My grace is sufficient for you, for My strength is made perfect in weakness.' Therefore most gladly I will rather boast in my infirmities, that the power of Christ may rest upon me. ...I take pleasure in infirmities, in reproaches, in needs, in persecutions, in distresses, for Christ’s sake. For when I am weak, then I am strong."

So this week, use your anger as motivation to rant to God, your sadness to cry to Him, your pain to reach out for Him, your happiness to praise Him, or your distance from Him as a conversation-starter.

God is big enough to handle all your feelings, and you are never safer than when you are praying in the presence of the Lord.

In short, the gospel reminds us that victory over temptation is easier than we think - it’s not about ignoring our feelings and trying to tough things out ourselves - its about using those feelings as motivation to run to God for His strength.

That's all for this week, thanks so much for reading to the end! If you've been blessed by this good news from the word of God, don't hesitate to share this email with your friends and family. Also, I'd love to hear your thoughts on today's topic. Let's chat at gomezdn7@gmail.com.

If you'd like to stop receiving these emails, send "stop" to gomezdn7@gmail.com

Yours in the blessed hope,

David
